What are NLP and text analysis?

  • Natural Language Processing (NLP) is a host of methods and disciplines, at the crossroad of :

    • data science
    • computational linguistics
    • artificial intelligence

  • NLPs main focus is processing all forms of human language (spoken or written) and getting insightful information out of it

  • Text analysis is a part of NLP and we can use it for written text

What is NLP used for?

  • NLP is used for:

    • Generating human speech
    • Automating tasks like machine translation
    • Producing predictive models or detecting patterns in human language

Why text analysis?

  • Most of the information and knowledge in the world is stored as text

Since most of the information and knowledge in the world is stored in a text format, the applications of text mining are everywhere around us: from auto-generated ads to detection of suicidal behavior through analyzing social media posts, from ubiquitous spam filters to uncovering plagiarism and the list goes on.

Text analysis : What it is ?

  • Text Analysis (TA) is an application of machine learning designed to derive meaningful information from unstructured textual data

  • Text analysis solutions are deployed to efficiently process and analyze vast quantities of online data and documents, converting them into practical insights

  • Text analysis can be employed to identify particular elements such as keywords, names, or corporate details within a massive volume of emails, or to classify feedback from surveys according to sentiment and subject matter

Text analysis: more advanced methods

  • Once you have scraped, cleaned, organized, visualized, and summarized data, more complex methods can be used


More advanced text analysis methods include document classification, entity extraction, sentiment analysis, word embeddings, and topic modeling to name a few.

Text analysis: use cases

Field Use case
Natural language processing Discover patterns in speech; understand how human language works
Business Help increase profits through analyzing product reviews; summarize and group reports, catalog documents
Psychology & Psychiatry Analyze sentiments to detect and prevent dangerous social behavior
Network analysis Augment network analysis to better understand how people interact within a group or react to a certain event

Its really difficult to overestimate the importance of text mining or text analysis, because human language and text, as one of its by-products, is the universal tool we use in every aspect of our daily lives. No wonder Alan Turing, the father of artificial intelligence, proposed in his famous paper* that the ability of a machine to understand and manipulate human language as skillfully as people do equates to the ability of a machine to think.

*Turing, Alan (October 1950), Computing Machinery and Intelligence, Mind, LIX (236): 433-460, doi:10.1093/mind/LIX.236.433, ISSN 0026-4423, retrieved 2016-10-17

Units of text data

Before we get to manipulate text data, Ill introduce you to some terms and concepts we will use. We know that letters make words, words, in turn, make utterances and sentences, and then sentences make passages and documents. These are some simple truths weve known since our early school years as we were learning how to read and write. We are used to thinking of text as a single document that we read, write or type. In text analysis, though, we will be looking at text from a slightly different viewpoint.

Units of text data: corpus

In a way, a corpus is like a big country consisting of different states much like the 50 states that make the United States a federation: they are all different, but they share some common characteristics like currency, official language, culture and others that make the US unique and recognizable as a whole.

Units of text data: corpora

We will treat text as a collection of documents. This collection is called a corpus (or corpora, in plural form). Corpus is a word that came to the English language from Latin and it means a body. We can think of a corpus as a large body of text, which, despite being put together from disparate pieces, has some distinct features that every document in that collection shares.
